description: Indian Roundleaf Bat or Kelaart's Leaf Nosed Bat (Hipposideros lankadiva) in a cave W.Ghats bordering Goa-Karnataka, with Dr. Deepak Deshpande, Shot taken without flash. Thanks to Rohit Chakrabarti for identification help.

Schneider's Leaf-nosed Bat or Schneider's Roundleaf Bat (Hipposideros speoris).

Range Description: This species is endemic to South Aisa and is presently known from India (Andhra Pradesh, Gujarat, Karnataka, Kerala, Maharashtra, Orissa, Tamil Nadu and Uttarakhand) and Sri Lanka (Central, Eastern, Sabaragamuwa, Southern, Uva and Western provinces) (Molur et al. 2002). It has been recorded up to an elevation of 1,385 m asl.

Taxonomic Notes: Earlier treated as a subspecies (Ellerman and Morrison-Scott 1951, Corbet and Hill 1992), the taxon pulchellus Andersen, 1918, is now synonymized with Hipposideros speoris (Schneider, 1800) (Sinha 1976, Koopman 1993, Bates and Harrison 1997, Simmons 2005) (Srinivasulu et al. in press).

indian fruit bat,
indian fruit bat,

There were many of these hanging from a banyan tree. The last pic can give an idea as to how many of them were hanging from each area of the tree. Also known as the Greater Indian Fruit Bat, it lives in mainly forests. It is a very large bat with a wing span of between 1.2 and 1.5 meters (4-5 feet). It is nocturnal and feeds mainly on ripe fruits such as mangoes and bananas and nectar. This bat is gregarious and lives in colonies which can number a few hundred. They have one to two young. They live in tropical forests and swamps, where there is a large body of water nearby.

description: ***IDENTIFICATION PROVISIONAL*** Comments sought, despite low quality photos taken using phone through telescope. Marginally better video at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sR0Wje_1v-E. At least three individuals of small-medium megabat feeding on figs, all media of the same individual which returned to the same spot to eat over a couple of hours. All dark brown pelage, lacking bright rufous colouring to neck & contrasting white wing bones of Cynopterus. Ears appeared short and round, and muzzle not particularly long, which also doesn't seem to fit Cynopterus nor Rousettus leschenaultii. Habitat and elevation (patches of trees/secondary forest among plantations, 1000-1100 masl) also seems wrong for R. leschenaultii. I'm aware L. samlimalii is a seemingly rare species but struggling to see what else this could be.

description:
Roosting from the ceiling of a dilapidated cattle kraal. Upon close observation by us, the bat swivelled its ears outwards, perhaps receiving information from returning sound waves on the new objects in its vicinity. It did not attempt to flee and we left it as is after a few photos.

The individual was earlier identified as Rhinolophus luctus based on its dark pelage and shape of the nose leaf. However, a conversation with Dr. Rohit Chakravarty revealed that the Himalayan populations of R. luctus are now called R. perniger. Apparently R. luctus is restricted to South-east Asia.
